{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17602093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17602093"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:21:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:21:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15683"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15683"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.06,0.09,0.79,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8374"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71193"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8374"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15683"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56667"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5122"},{"type":"tags","id":"7607"},{"type":"tags","id":"10109"},{"type":"tags","id":"10121"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20182"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20185"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71193"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGrowth hormone secretion from the anterior pituitary is regulated by the hypothalamus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following hormones stimulates growth hormone production from the anterior pituitary?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Corticotropin releasing hormone","Adrenocorticotropic hormone","Thyrotropin releasing hormone","Growth hormone\u2013releasing hormone","Somatostatin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hypothalamus controls anterior pituitary hormone secretion through a system of releasing and inhibiting factors. Each anterior pituitary hormone responds to specific hypothalamic signals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorticotropin releasing hormone\u003C/strong\u003E triggers ACTH production\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenocorticotropic hormone\u003C/strong\u003E is not a hypothalamic hormone but rather a pituitary hormone that acts on the adrenal glands\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyrotropin releasing hormone\u003C/strong\u003E controls TSH production\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth hormone-releasing hormone\u003C/strong\u003E specifically triggers growth hormone synthesis and release\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESomatostatin\u003C/strong\u003E acts as a brake on growth hormone secretion\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis system allows precise control over growth hormone levels through both stimulatory and inhibitory signals from the hypothalamus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Growth hormone secretion is stimulated by growth hormone releasing hormone from the hypothalamus","Growth hormone release is under dual control - stimulation by growth hormone releasing hormone and inhibition by somatostatin","Each anterior pituitary hormone is regulated by specific hypothalamic releasing factors"],"references":["Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA.","Kovacs, W. J., \u0026 Ojeda, S. R. (Eds.). (2012). Textbook of endocrine physiology. OUP USA."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56667"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15683"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56667"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T19:49:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T19:49:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8374"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71193"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6d","name":"Endocrine","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-3